**AS 1000** — *General Responsibilities of the Auditor in Conducting an Audit* — is the PCAOB Auditing Standard that establishes the auditor's general principles and responsibilities applicable in all audits.

As stated in the standard, it "describes the general principles and responsibilities of the auditor in properly conducting an audit in accordance with the standards of the PCAOB," sets out the objectives of the auditor, and establishes requirements for the auditor's professional qualifications and general responsibilities [AS 1000.02].

Among these general responsibilities, AS 1000 requires the auditor to exercise **due professional care**, which includes exercising **professional skepticism**. Professional skepticism is described as an attitude that includes a questioning mind and a critical assessment of audit evidence and other information. It encompasses [AS 1000.11]:

- Objectively evaluating evidence — both corroborating and contradicting management's assertions — and considering its sufficiency and appropriateness (relevance and reliability);
- Remaining alert to conditions that may indicate possible misstatement due to error or fraud;
- Not being satisfied with evidence that is less than persuasive;
- Not assuming that management is honest or dishonest; and
- Considering potential bias on the part of both management and the auditor.

This due-care/skepticism requirement carries through to other standards as well — for example, AS 2401 cross-references AS 1000.09 and .11 when emphasizing the importance of professional skepticism in considering fraud risks [AS 2401.13].
